gr; Molecular evolution of the metallothionein. Suggestions for a natural 
gr; classification system.
gr; FOURTH INTERNATIONAL MEETING ON METALLOTHIONEIN, KANSAS CITY (USA), 1997.
bb;
bb;
gd; Metallothioneins (MT) are small proteins that bind heavy metals, such as
gd; zinc, copper, cadmium, nickel, etc.. They have a high content of cysteine
gd; residues that bind the metal ions through clusters of thiolate bonds [1-3]
gd; (http://www.unizh.ch/~mtpage/MT.html). An empirical classification into
gd; three classes has been proposed by Fowler et al. [4] and Kojima [5]. Members
gd; of class I are defined to include polypeptides related in the positions of
gd; their cysteines to equine MT-1B, and include mammalian MTs as well as MTs 
gd; from crustaceans and molluscs. Class II groups MTs from a variety of 
gd; species, including sea urchins, fungi, insects and cyanobacteria. Class
gd; III MTs are atypical polypeptides composed of gamma-glutamylcysteinyl
gd; units [4]. 
gd;
gd; This original classification system has been found to be limited, in the
gd; sense that it does not allow clear differentiation of patterns of structural
gd; similarities, either between or within classes. Consequently, all class I
gd; and class II MTs (the proteinaceous sequences) have now been grouped into
gd; families of phylogenetically-related and thus alignable sequences [6]
gd; (http://www.unizh.ch/~mtpage/classif.html). This system subdivides the MT
gd; superfamily into families, subfamilies, subgroups, and isolated isoforms
gd; and alleles. 
gd;
gd; The metallothionein superfamily comprises all polypeptides that resemble
gd; equine renal metallothionein in several respects [4]: e.g., low molecular
gd; weight; high metal content; amino acid composition with high Cys and low
gd; aromatic residue content; unique sequence with characteristic distribution
gd; of cysteines, and spectroscopic manifestations indicative of metal thiolate
gd; clusters. A MT family subsumes MTs that share particular sequence-specific 
gd; features and are thought to be evolutionarily related. The inclusion of a
gd; MT within a family presupposes that its amino acid sequence is alignable 
gd; with that of all members. Fifteen MT families have been characterised, each
gd; family being identified by its number and its taxonomic range: e.g., Family
gd; 1: vertebrate MTs.
gd;
gd; Echinoidea (Sea urchin, family 4) MTs are 64-67 residue proteins, in which
gd; 20 conserved cysteines bind divalent metal ions. The protein is arranged
gd; into two domains, the N-terminal domain containing 9 Cys residues and the
gd; C-terminal domain having 11 cysteines. In particular, the consensus pattern 
gd; P-D-x-K-C-V-C-C-x(5)-C-x-C-x(4)-C-C-x(4)-C-C-x(4,6)-C-C has been found to
gd; be diagnostic of family 4 MTs. The protein is induced by and binds various
gd; heavy metal ions.
gd;
gd; MTECHINOIDEA is a 4-element fingerprint that provides a signature for
gd; echinoidea (sea urchin, family 4) metallothioneins. The fingerprint was
gd; derived from an initial alignment of 6 sequences: motif 1 contains 5 metal-
gd; binding Cys residues; motifs 2 and 3 each include 4 cysteines; and motif 4
gd; contains 6 Cys residues. Motifs 1 to 3 fully span the characteristic
gd; consensus pattern. Two iterations on OWL30.1 were required to reach
gd; convergence, at which point a true set comprising 7 sequences was 
gd; identified.
gd;
gd; An update on SPTR37_9f identified a true set of 5 sequences.
